On 24.3.2009 vote of confidence was held in the Chamber of Deputies, initiated by the opposition parties ČSSD and KSCM, and the Chamber expressed no confidence. It was first government in the history of the Czech Republic which was overthrown by the vote of non-confidence. There were 101 MPs for the non-confidence expression, 96 MPs against.  In addition to all deputies from opposition ČSSD  (71) and KSCM (26) voted against the government also two rebels from ODS Vlastimil Tlustý and Jan Schwippel and two former deputies for SZ - Vera Jakubková and Olga Zubová.

On the 3rd April 2012, the leaders of VV announced that their ministers will leave the government by the 1st May. However, one day later all 3 ministers of VV (2 of them are not MPs) led by deputy prime minister Karolina Peake announced that they refused to resign. On the 17th April Peake stated that she was leaving VV and was establishing a new fraction called LIDEM, which is meant to support the Nečas cabinet. In the following days she succeeded in gaining support from 7 other VV MPs, who consequently left the PPG of VV. The LIDEM fraction officially turned to become a party on the 29th May 2012, when it was registered by the Ministry of Interior as a political party

PM Petr Nečas resigned on 17.6. 2013 after his closest co-worker, the Managing Director of the Section of the PM Jana Nagyova was put under arrest and accused of misuse of the Millitary Intelligence Agency which should be following up Nečas’ wife. The police also suspects Nagyova of corruption behaviour consisting in organizing high-profile posts in state-owned enterprises for three former ODS factioning MP`s who opposed the state budget bill and later have voluntarily resigned on their MP mandate and so enabled that the Nečas cabinet bill on state budget was passed. The arrest of Nagyova was a part of a larger anti-corruption police operation and included prosecution of former MPs, Military Intelligence officials and influential businessmen suspect of manipulating state tenders
